      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The distinction between a \"living constitution\" and judicial bias often hinges on the methodology used by the judges. Those supporting a living constitution argue that the document must adapt to evolving societal norms and circumstances to remain relevant, which is a legitimate judicial function. However, critics claim this flexibility allows judges to substitute their personal political ideologies for the fixed text, which is what they mean by judicial overreach or bias. The key difference lies in whether the interpretation is argued as a necessary evolution of the law or as a policy preference imposed from the bench.",
